@isabelclanc + Mike have been through so much together. In the time since they met at 19 and 20, they have conquered so many things by each other’s side. They have started a family together. They have created a community together. While many of us were figuring our lives out, I+M were building something. Something so special that you could feel it everywhere they were - from their getting ready space to their dance floor. I+M are certainly the life of the party, but I think my favorite moment of the day was during portraits. Jesse and @ophotocapecod were taking photos of Isabel. As they were doing that, my attention went to their three kids. There they were, sitting huddled into each other watching a video on a phone. There was something really telling about their relationships that I noticed then. There was no bickering, no yelling, no fighting for attention between them. They all shared the same space - kindly, peacefully, and affectionately. Just as Isabel greeted every single person (vendors included) with the utmost joy and affection, her kids modeled that behavior between each other and everyone around them. This is what it’s like to be around I+M - you are welcomed and you are loved.

About the film: “They say when you meet the love of your life, time stops, and that’s true. What they don’t tell you is that when it starts again, it moves extra fast to catch up” - Big Fish. As tends to happen when I’m taking a quick break from editing, I get lost in a YouTube rabbit hole of old movie clips. Rewatching work I admire always produces some nugget of inspiration and this one seemed particularly apropos given I + M’s story. This was a story not about the initial explosion of romance but of the stunning little moments we get along the way. There is an ever present ticking clock and ticking of clips as if to say, “see these moments, hold them close”. I deliberately slowed my pacing down and let moments linger longer than I typically would. Like a long embrace or a dance with your child, I wanted these moments to feel like a respite from the deluge of daily events; a chance to reflect on everything that got them there - something all five of them could treasure.
